By this verse, even more directly than by the preceding proposition. the poet shuts out from his system the pos· sibility of the existence oi God or spirit in the ordinary sense oi the term. All phenomena, as he proceeds to explain, are reducible to states and relations oi matter and void ; as matter is the only reality, in the end phenomena reduce to states oi matter. This is precisely the position oi modern materialists. cf. Herbert Spencer, ‘Prin of Psychology,’ i. p. 267: “Itis one and the same Ultimate ,Realrty which is manifested to us subjectively and objectively.
